🧠 1. What is a Stack? (Definition)
💬 Say this

“A stack is a linear data structure that follows LIFO (Last In First Out). The last element inserted is the first one to be removed.”

🧠 2. Why use a Stack? (VERY IMPORTANT)
💬 Strong interview answer

“I use a stack when I need to track elements in a last-in-first-out manner, especially when solving problems involving nested structures, backtracking, or maintaining a history of elements waiting to be processed.”

🔥 When stack is the RIGHT choice
1. Matching / nested → parentheses, expressions
2. Undo / rollback → browser history
3. Monotonic behavior → next greater/smaller
4. DFS traversal → recursion replacement
5. Expression evaluation → postfix/prefix
🧠 3. Why stack over other data structures?
💬 Answer like this

“Stack is useful when the most recent element is the most relevant one. Unlike arrays or queues, it gives O(1) access to the latest unresolved element.”

⚖️ Comparison intuition
Structure	When to use
Stack	recent element matters
Queue	order matters (FIFO)
Array/List	random access needed
Heap	need min/max quickly
HashMap	fast lookup
🧠 4. Time Complexity (IMPORTANT)
Operations:
push() → O(1)
pop() → O(1)
peek() → O(1)
💬 Why O(1)?

“Because stack operations only interact with the top element, and no shifting or traversal is required.”

⚠️ Follow-up they may ask:

“What about dynamic resizing?”

👉 Answer:

“If implemented using an array, resizing can take O(n), but amortized complexity remains O(1).”

🧠 5. Space Complexity
Stack uses O(n) space
💬 Say:

“In worst case, all elements may be stored in the stack.”

🧠 6. Stack vs Queue (VERY COMMON)
Feature	Stack	Queue
Order	LIFO	FIFO
Insert	top	rear
Remove	top	front
Use case	recursion, undo	scheduling, buffering
💬 Interview answer

“Stack processes most recent elements first, while queue processes elements in arrival order.”

🧠 7. Implement Stack using Queue
💡 Idea

Make queue behave like stack by rotating elements

✅ Code (one queue)
id="r6xwja"
class MyStack {
    Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();

    public void push(int x) {
        q.add(x);
        int size = q.size();

        // rotate previous elements
        for (int i = 0; i < size - 1; i++) {
            q.add(q.remove());
        }
    }

    public int pop() {
        return q.remove();
    }

    public int top() {
        return q.peek();
    }

    public boolean empty() {
        return q.isEmpty();
    }
}
💬 Explain like this

“After inserting, I rotate the queue so the newest element comes to the front, mimicking stack behavior.”

🧠 8. Implement Queue using Stack
💡 Idea

Use two stacks:

inStack → push
outStack → pop
✅ Code
id="a3v8yt"
class MyQueue {
    Stack<Integer> in = new Stack<>();
    Stack<Integer> out = new Stack<>();

    public void push(int x) {
        in.push(x);
    }

    public int pop() {
        if (out.isEmpty()) {
            while (!in.isEmpty()) {
                out.push(in.pop());
            }
        }
        return out.pop();
    }

    public int peek() {
        if (out.isEmpty()) {
            while (!in.isEmpty()) {
                out.push(in.pop());
            }
        }
        return out.peek();
    }

    public boolean empty() {
        return in.isEmpty() && out.isEmpty();
    }
}
💬 Explain like this

“We reverse order using two stacks to simulate FIFO behavior.”

🧠 9. Monotonic Stack (MOST IMPORTANT CONCEPT)
💬 Say:

“A monotonic stack maintains elements in increasing or decreasing order and is used to efficiently find next greater or smaller elements.”

Types:
Increasing stack
Decreasing stack
Where used:
Next Greater Element
Stock Span
Daily Temperatures
Histogram
🧠 10. Stack vs Recursion
💬 Say:

“Recursion internally uses a call stack. We can replace recursion with an explicit stack for better control.”

🧠 11. Real-world uses (interviewer may ask)
Undo/Redo (editors)
Browser history
Expression parsing
Backtracking (DFS)
Syntax parsing (compilers)
🧠 12. Common Interview Questions

You should be ready to answer:

❓ Why stack here?

“We need to process elements in reverse order of arrival / maintain unresolved elements.”

❓ Why not queue?

“Queue processes oldest first, but here we need most recent element first.”

❓ Why not array?

“We need dynamic push/pop from one end efficiently without shifting.”

